{"text": "1.8  Electric Field
Let us consider a point charge Q placed in vacuum, at the origin O.", "fibs": ["point"]}
{"text": "If we place another point charge q at a point P, where OP = r, then the charge Q will exert a force on q as per Coulomb’s law.", "fibs": ["place"]}
{"text": "We may ask the question: If charge q is removed, then what is left in the surrounding?", "fibs": ["question"]}
{"text": "Is there nothing?", "fibs": ["nothing"]}
{"text": "If there is nothing at the point P, then how does a force act when we place the charge q at P. In order to answer such questions, the early scientists introduced the concept of field.", "fibs": ["nothing"]}
{"text": "According to this, we say that the charge Q produces an electric field everywhere in the surrounding.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "When another charge q is brought at some point P, the field there acts on it and produces a force.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "The electric field produced by the charge Q  at a point r is given as
