Note that the charge q also exerts an equal and opposite force on the charge Q.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "The electrostatic force between the charges Q and q can be looked upon as an interaction between charge q and the electric field of Q and vice versa.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "If we denote the position of charge q by the vector r, it experiences a force F equal to the charge q multiplied by the electric field E at the location of q.", "fibs": ["position"]}
{"text": "Thus,
F(r) = q E(r)	(1.8)
Equation (1.8) defines the SI unit of electric field as N/C*.", "fibs": ["F(r"]}
{"text": "Some important remarks may be made here:
(i) From Eq.", "fibs": ["Eq."]}
{"text": "(1.8), we can infer that if q is unity, the electric field due to a charge Q is numerically equal to the force exerted by it.", "fibs": ["1.8)"]}
{"text": "Thus, the electric field due to a charge Q at a point in space may be defined as the force that a unit positive charge would experience if placed at that point.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "The charge Q, which is producing the electric field, is called a source charge and the charge q, which tests the effect of a source charge, is called a test charge.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "Note that the source charge Q must remain at its original location.", "fibs": ["source"]}
{"text": "However, if a charge q is brought at any point around Q, Q itself is bound to experience an electrical force due to q and will tend to move.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "A way out of this difficulty is to make q negligibly small.", "fibs": ["way"]}
{"text": "The force F is then negligibly small but the ratio F/q is finite and defines the electric field: 
	(1.9)






Figure 1.11 Electric field (a) due to a charge Q, (b) due to a charge –Q.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "A practical way to get around the problem (of keeping Q undisturbed in the presence of q) is to hold Q to its location by unspecified forces!", "fibs": ["way"]}
{"text": "This may look strange but actually this is what happens in practice.", "fibs": ["practice"]}
{"text": "When we are considering the electric force on a test charge q due to a charged planar sheet (Section 1.15), the charges on the sheet are held to their locations by the forces due to the unspecified charged constituents inside the sheet.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "(ii) Note that the electric field E due to Q, though defined operationally in terms of some test charge q, is independent of q.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "This is because F is proportional to q, so the ratio F/q does not depend on q.", "fibs": ["F"]}
{"text": "The force F on the charge q due to the charge Q depends on the particular location of charge q which may take any value in the space around the charge Q.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "Thus, the electric field E due to Q is also dependent on the space coordinate r. For different positions of the charge q all over the space, we get different values of electric field E. The field exists at every point in three-dimensional space.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "(iii) For a positive charge, the electric field will be directed radially outwards from the charge.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "On the other hand, if the source charge is negative, the electric field vector, at each point, points radially inwards.", "fibs": ["hand"]}
{"text": "(iv) Since the magnitude of the force F on charge q due to charge Q depends only on the distance r of the charge q from charge Q, the magnitude of the electric field E will also depend only on the distance r. Thus at equal distances from the charge Q, the magnitude of its electric field E is same.", "fibs": ["iv"]}
{"text": "The magnitude of electric field E due to a point charge is thus same on a sphere with the point charge at its centre; in other words, it has a spherical symmetry.", "fibs": ["magnitude"]}
