{"text": "1.8.2 Physical significance of electric field
You may wonder why the notion of electric field has been introduced here at all.", "fibs": ["significance"]}
{"text": "After all, for any system of charges, the measurable quantity is the force on a charge which can be directly determined using Coulomb’s law and the superposition principle [Eq.", "fibs": ["system"]}
{"text": "Why then introduce this intermediate quantity called the electric field?", "fibs": ["quantity"]}
{"text": "For electrostatics, the concept of electric field is convenient, but not really necessary.", "fibs": ["concept"]}
{"text": "Electric field is an elegant way of characterising the electrical environment of a system of charges.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "Electric field at a point in the space around a system of charges tells you the force a unit positive test charge would experience if placed at that point (without disturbing the system).", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "Electric field is a characteristic of the system of charges and is independent of the test charge that you place at a point to determine the field.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "The term field in physics generally refers to a quantity that is defined at every point in space and may vary from point to point.", "fibs": ["term"]}
{"text": "Electric field is a vector field, since force is a vector quantity.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "Figure 1.12 Electric field at a point due to a system of charges is the vector sum of the electric fields at the point due to individual charges.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "The true physical significance of the concept of electric field, however, emerges only when we go beyond electrostatics and deal with time-dependent electromagnetic phenomena.", "fibs": ["significance"]}
{"text": "Suppose we consider the force between two distant charges q1, q2 in accelerated motion.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "Now the greatest speed with which a signal or information can go from one point to another is c, the speed of light.", "fibs": ["speed"]}
{"text": "Thus, the effect of any motion of q1 on q2 cannot arise instantaneously.", "fibs": ["effect"]}
{"text": "There will be some time delay between the effect (force on q2) and the cause (motion of q1).", "fibs": ["time"]}
{"text": "It is precisely here that the notion of electric field (strictly, electromagnetic field) is natural and very useful.", "fibs": ["notion"]}
{"text": "The field picture is this: the accelerated motion of charge q1 produces electromagnetic waves, which then propagate with the speed c, reach q2 and cause a force on q2.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "The notion of field elegantly accounts for the time delay.", "fibs": ["notion"]}
{"text": "They can also transport energy.", "fibs": ["transport"]}
{"text": "Thus, a source of time-dependent electromagnetic fields, turned on for a short interval of time and then switched off, leaves behind propagating electromagnetic fields transporting energy.", "fibs": ["source"]}
{"text": "The concept of field was first introduced by Faraday and is now among the central concepts in physics.", "fibs": ["concept"]}
