{"text": "Superposition Principle: The principle is based on the property that the forces with which two charges attract or repel each other are not affected by the presence of a third (or more) additional charge(s).", "fibs": ["Superposition"]}
{"text": "For an assembly of charges q1, q2, q3, ..., the force on any charge, say q1, is the vector sum of the force on  q1 due to q2, the force on q1 due to q3, and so on.", "fibs": ["assembly"]}
{"text": "For each pair, the force is given by the Coulomb’s law for two charges stated earlier.", "fibs": ["pair"]}
{"text": "The electric field E at a point due to a charge configuration is the force on a small positive test charge q placed at the point divided by the magnitude of the charge.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "Electric field due to a point charge q has a magnitude |q|/4πε0r2; it is radially outwards from q, if q is positive, and radially inwards if q is negative.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "Like Coulomb force, electric field also satisfies superposition principle.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "An electric field line is a curve drawn in such a way that the tangent at each point on the curve gives the direction of electric field at that point.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "The relative closeness of field lines indicates the relative strength of electric field at different points; they crowd near each other in regions of strong electric field and are far apart where the electric field is weak.", "fibs": ["closeness"]}
{"text": "In regions of constant electric field, the field lines are uniformly spaced parallel straight lines.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "On symmetry operations
In Physics, we often encounter systems with various symmetries.", "fibs": ["symmetry"]}
{"text": "Consideration of these symmetries helps one arrive at results much faster than otherwise by a straightforward calculation.", "fibs": ["Consideration"]}
{"text": "Consider, for example an infinite uniform sheet of charge (surface charge density σ) along the y-z plane.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "This system is unchanged if (a) translated parallel to the y-z plane in any direction, (b) rotated about the x-axis through any angle.", "fibs": ["system"]}
{"text": "As the system is unchanged under such symmetry operation, so must its properties be.", "fibs": ["system"]}
{"text": "In particular, in this example, the electric field E must be unchanged.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Translation symmetry along the y-axis shows that the electric field must be the same at a point (0, y1, 0) as at (0, y2, 0).", "fibs": ["symmetry"]}
{"text": "Similarly translational symmetry along the z-axis shows that the electric field at two point (0, 0, z1) and (0, 0, z2) must be the same.", "fibs": ["symmetry"]}
{"text": "By using rotation symmetry around the x-axis, we can conclude that E must be perpendicular to the y-z plane, that is, it must be parallel to the x-direction.", "fibs": ["rotation"]}
{"text": "Try to think of a symmetry now which will tell you that the magnitude of the electric field is a constant, independent of the x-coordinate.", "fibs": ["symmetry"]}
{"text": "It thus turns out that the magnitude of the electric field due to a uniformly charged infinite conducting sheet is the same at all points in space.", "fibs": ["magnitude"]}
{"text": "The direction, however, is opposite of each other on either side ofthe sheet.", "fibs": ["direction"]}
{"text": "Compare this with the effort needed to arrive at this result by a direct calculation using Coulomb’s law.", "fibs": ["effort"]}
{"text": "Some of the important properties of field lines are: (i) Field lines are continuous curves without any breaks.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "(ii) Two field lines cannot cross each other.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "(iii) Electrostatic field lines start at positive charges and end at negative charges —they cannot form closed loops.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "An electric dipole is a pair of equal and opposite charges q and –q separated by some distance 2a.", "fibs": ["pair"]}
{"text": "Its dipole moment vector p has magnitude 2qa and is in the direction of the dipole axis from –q to q.", "fibs": ["moment"]}
