{"text": "You might wonder why the protons, all carrying positive charges, are compactly residing inside the nucleus.", "fibs": ["wonder"]}
{"text": "You will learn that there is a third kind of a fundamental force, called the strong force which holds them together.", "fibs": ["kind"]}
{"text": "The range of distance where this force is effective is, however, very small ~10-14 m. This is precisely the size of the nucleus.", "fibs": ["range"]}
{"text": "inside the nucleus, due to the laws of quantum mechanics.", "fibs": ["nucleus"]}
{"text": "This gives the atoms their structure as they exist in nature.", "fibs": ["structure"]}
{"text": "Coulomb force and gravitational force follow the same inverse-square law.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "But gravitational force has only one sign (always attractive), while Coulomb force can be of both signs (attractive and repulsive), allowing possibility of cancellation of electric forces.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "This is how gravity, despite being a much weaker force, can be a dominating and more pervasive force in nature.", "fibs": ["gravity"]}
{"text": "The constant of proportionality k in Coulomb’s law is a matter of choice if the unit of charge is to be defined using Coulomb’s law.", "fibs": ["proportionality"]}
{"text": "In SI units, however, what is defined is the unit of current (A) via its magnetic effect (Ampere’s law) and the unit of charge (coulomb) is simply defined by (1C = 1 A s).", "fibs": ["SI"]}
{"text": "In this case, the value of k is no longer arbitrary; it is approximately 9 × 109 N m2 C–2.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "The rather large value of k, i.e., the large size of the unit of charge (1C) from the point of view of electric effects arises because (as mentioned in point 3 already) the unit of charge is defined in terms of magnetic forces (forces on  current–carrying wires) which are generally much weaker than the electric forces.", "fibs": ["value"]}
{"text": "Thus while 1 ampere is a unit of reasonable size for magnetic effects, 1 C = 1 A s, is too big a unit for electric effects.", "fibs": ["ampere"]}
{"text": "The additive property of charge is not an ‘obvious’ property.", "fibs": ["additive"]}
{"text": "It is related to the fact that electric charge has no direction associated with it; charge is a scalar.", "fibs": ["fact"]}
{"text": "Charge is not only a scalar (or invariant) under rotation; it is also invariant for frames of reference in relative motion.", "fibs": ["rotation"]}
{"text": "For example, kinetic energy is a scalar under rotation, but is not invariant for frames of reference in relative motion.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Conservation of total charge of an isolated system is a property independent of the scalar nature of charge noted in point 6.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "Conservation refers to invariance in time in a given frame of reference.", "fibs": ["invariance"]}
{"text": "A quantity may be scalar but not conserved (like kinetic energy in an inelastic collision).", "fibs": ["quantity"]}
{"text": "On the other hand, one can have conserved vector quantity (e.g., angular momentum of an isolated system).", "fibs": ["hand"]}
{"text": "Quantisation of electric charge is a basic (unexplained) law of nature; interestingly, there is no analogous law on quantisation of mass.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "Superposition principle should not be regarded as ‘obvious’, or equated with the law of addition of vectors.", "fibs": ["Superposition"]}
{"text": "It says two things: force on one charge due to another charge is unaffected by the presence of other charges, and there are no additional three-body, four-body, etc., forces which arise only when there are more than two charges.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "The electric field due to a discrete charge configuration is not defined at the locations of the discrete charges.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "For continuous volume charge distribution, it is defined at any point in the distribution.", "fibs": ["volume"]}
{"text": "For a surface charge distribution, electric field is discontinuous across the surface.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "The electric field due to a charge configuration with total charge zero is not zero; but for distances large compared to the size of the configuration, its field falls off faster than 1/r2, typical of field due to a single charge.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "An electric dipole is the simplest example of this fact.", "fibs": ["example"]}
