Chapter One

ELECTRIC CHARGES AND FIELDS





1.1  Introduction



All of us have the experience of seeing a spark or hearing a crackle when we take off our synthetic clothes or sweater, particularly in dry weather.", "fibs": ["Example"]}
{"text": "This is almost inevitable with ladies garments like a polyester saree.", "fibs": ["polyester"]}
{"text": "Have you ever tried to find any explanation for this phenomenon?", "fibs": ["explanation"]}
{"text": "Another common example of electric discharge is the lightning that we see in the sky during thunderstorms.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "We also experience a sensation of an electric shock either while opening the door of a car or holding the iron bar of a bus after sliding from our seat.", "fibs": ["experience"]}
{"text": "The reason for these experiences is discharge of electric charges through our body, which were accumulated due to rubbing of insulating surfaces.", "fibs": ["reason"]}
{"text": "You might have also heard that this is due to generation of static electricity.", "fibs": ["generation"]}
{"text": "This is precisely the topic we are going to discuss in this and the next chapter.", "fibs": ["topic"]}
{"text": "Static means anything that does not move or change with time.", "fibs": ["anything"]}
{"text": "Electrostatics deals with the study of forces, fields and potentials arising from static charges.", "fibs": ["study"]}
{"text": "1.2  Electric Charge
Historically the credit of discovery of the fact that amber rubbed with wool or silk cloth attracts light objects goes to Thales of Miletus, Greece, around 600 BC.", "fibs": ["credit"]}
{"text": "The name electricity is coined from the Greek word elektron meaning amber.", "fibs": ["name"]}
{"text": "Many such pairs of materials were known which on rubbing could attract light objects like straw, pith balls and bits of papers.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "You can perform the following activity at home to experience such an effect.", "fibs": ["activity"]}
{"text": "Cut out long thin strips of white paper and lightly iron them.", "fibs": ["paper"]}
{"text": "Take them near a TV screen or computer monitor.", "fibs": ["TV"]}
{"text": "You will see that the strips get attracted to the screen.", "fibs": ["screen"]}
{"text": "In fact they remain stuck to the screen for a while.", "fibs": ["fact"]}
{"text": "Figure 1.1 Rods and pith balls: like charges repel and unlike charges attract each other.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "It was observed that if two glass rods rubbed with wool or silk cloth are brought close to each other, they repel each other [Fig.", "fibs": ["glass"]}
{"text": "1.1(a)].", "fibs": ["1.1(a"]}
{"text": "The two strands of wool or two pieces of silk cloth, with which the rods were rubbed, also repel each other.", "fibs": ["wool"]}
{"text": "However, the glass rod and wool attracted each other.", "fibs": ["glass"]}
{"text": "Similarly, two plastic rods rubbed with cat’s fur repelled each other [Fig.", "fibs": ["plastic"]}
{"text": "1.1(b)] but attracted the fur.", "fibs": ["1.1(b"]}
{"text": "On the other hand, the plastic rod attracts the glass rod [Fig.", "fibs": ["hand"]}
{"text": "1.1(c)] and repel the silk or wool with which the glass rod is rubbed.", "fibs": ["1.1(c"]}
{"text": "The glass rod repels the fur.", "fibs": ["glass"]}
{"text": "If a plastic rod rubbed with fur is made to touch two small pith balls (now-a-days we can use polystyrene balls) suspended by silk or nylon thread, then the balls repel each other [Fig.", "fibs": ["plastic"]}
{"text": "1.1(d)] and are also repelled by the rod.", "fibs": ["1.1(d"]}
{"text": "A similar effect is found if the pith balls are touched with a glass rod rubbed with silk [Fig.", "fibs": ["effect"]}
{"text": "1.1(e)].", "fibs": ["1.1(e"]}
{"text": "A dramatic observation is that a pith ball touched with glass rod attracts another pith ball touched with plastic rod [Fig.", "fibs": ["observation"]}
{"text": "1.1(f)].", "fibs": ["1.1(f"]}
{"text": "It was concluded, after many careful studies by different scientists, that there were only two kinds of an entity which is called the electric charge.", "fibs": ["entity"]}
{"text": "We say that the bodies like glass or plastic rods, silk, fur and pith balls are electrified.", "fibs": ["glass"]}
{"text": "They acquire an electric charge on rubbing.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "The experiments on pith balls suggested that there are two kinds of electrification and we find  that (i) like charges repel and (ii) unlike charges attract each other.", "fibs": ["pith"]}
{"text": "The experiments also demonstrated that the charges are transferred from the rods to the pith balls on  contact.", "fibs": ["pith"]}
{"text": "It is said that the pith balls are electrified or are charged by  contact.", "fibs": ["pith"]}
{"text": "The property which differentiates the two kinds of charges is called the polarity of charge.", "fibs": ["property"]}
{"text": "When a glass rod is rubbed with silk, the rod acquires one kind of charge and the silk acquires the second kind of charge.", "fibs": ["glass"]}
{"text": "This is true for any pair of objects that are rubbed to be electrified.", "fibs": ["pair"]}
{"text": "Now if the electrified glass rod is brought in contact with silk, with which it was rubbed, they no longer attract each other.", "fibs": ["glass"]}
{"text": "They also do not attract or repel other light objects as they did on being electrified.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "Thus, the charges acquired after rubbing are lost when the charged bodies are brought in contact.", "fibs": ["contact"]}
{"text": "It just tells us that unlike charges acquired by the objects neutralise or nullify each other’s effect.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "Therefore, the charges were named as positive and negative by the American scientist Benjamin Franklin.", "fibs": ["scientist"]}
{"text": "We know that when we add a positive number to a negative number of the same magnitude, the sum is zero.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "This might have been the philosophy in naming the charges as positive and negative.", "fibs": ["philosophy"]}
{"text": "By convention, the charge on glass rod or cat’s fur is called positive and that on plastic rod or silk is termed negative.", "fibs": ["convention"]}
{"text": "If an object possesses an electric charge, it is said to be electrified or charged.", "fibs": ["object"]}
{"text": "When it has no charge it is said to be electrically neutral.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "A simple apparatus to detect charge on a body is the gold-leaf electroscope [Fig.", "fibs": ["apparatus"]}
{"text": "1.2(a)].", "fibs": ["1.2(a"]}
{"text": "It consists of a vertical metal rod housed in a box, with two thin gold leaves attached to its bottom end.", "fibs": ["metal"]}
{"text": "When a charged object touches the metal knob at the top of the rod, charge flows on to the leaves and they diverge.", "fibs": ["object"]}
{"text": "The degree of divergance is an indicator of the amount of charge.", "fibs": ["degree"]}
{"text": "Unification of electricity and magnetism
In olden days, electricity and magnetism were treated as separate subjects.", "fibs": ["electricity"]}
{"text": "Electricity dealt with charges on glass rods, cat’s fur, batteries, lightning, etc., while magnetism described interactions of magnets, iron filings, compass needles, etc.", "fibs": ["glass"]}
{"text": "In 1820 Danish scientist Oersted found that a compass needle is deflected by passing an electric current through a wire placed near the needle.", "fibs": ["scientist"]}
{"text": "Ampere and Faraday supported this observation by saying that electric charges in motion produce magnetic fields and moving magnets generate electricity.", "fibs": ["observation"]}
{"text": "The unification was achieved when the Scottish physicist Maxwell and the Dutch physicist Lorentz put forward a theory where they showed the interdependence of these two subjects.", "fibs": ["unification"]}
{"text": "This field is called electromagnetism.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "Most of the phenomena occurring around us can be described under electromagnetism.", "fibs": ["electromagnetism"]}
{"text": "Virtually every force that we can think of like friction, chemical force between atoms holding the matter together, and even the forces describing processes occurring in cells of living organisms, have its origin in electromagnetic force.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "Electromagnetic force is one of the fundamental forces of nature.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "Maxwell put forth four equations that play the same role in classical electromagnetism as Newton’s equations of motion and gravitation law play in mechanics.", "fibs": ["role"]}
{"text": "He also argued that light is electromagnetic in nature and its speed can be found by making purely electric and magnetic measurements.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "He claimed that the science of optics is intimately related to that of electricity and magnetism.", "fibs": ["science"]}
{"text": "The science of electricity and magnetism is the foundation for the modern technological civilisation.", "fibs": ["science"]}
{"text": "Electric power, telecommunication, radio and television, and a wide variety of the practical appliances used in daily life are based on the principles of this science.", "fibs": ["power"]}
{"text": "Although charged particles in motion exert both electric and magnetic forces, in the frame of reference where all the charges are at rest, the forces are purely electrical.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "You know that gravitational force is a long-range force.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "Its effect is felt even when the distance between the interacting particles is very large because the force decreases inversely as the square of the distance between the interacting bodies.", "fibs": ["effect"]}
{"text": "We will learn in this chapter that electric force is also as pervasive and is in fact stronger than the gravitational force by several orders of magnitude (refer to Chapter 1 of Class XI Physics Textbook).", "fibs": ["chapter"]}
{"text": "Students can make a simple electroscope as follows [Fig.", "fibs": ["electroscope"]}
{"text": "1.2(b)]: Take a thin aluminium curtain rod with ball ends fitted for hanging the curtain.", "fibs": ["1.2(b"]}
{"text": "Cut out a piece of length about 20 cm with the ball at one end and flatten the cut end.", "fibs": ["piece"]}
{"text": "Take a large bottle that can hold this rod and a cork which will fit in the opening of the bottle.", "fibs": ["bottle"]}
{"text": "Make a hole in the cork sufficient to hold the curtain rod snugly.", "fibs": ["hole"]}
{"text": "Slide the rod through the hole in the cork with the cut end on the lower side and ball end projecting above the cork.", "fibs": ["Slide"]}
{"text": "Fold a small, thin aluminium foil (about 6 cm in length) in the middle and attach it to the flattened end of the rod by cellulose tape.", "fibs": ["aluminium"]}
{"text": "This forms the leaves of your electroscope.", "fibs": ["electroscope"]}
{"text": "Fit the cork in the bottle with about 5 cm of the ball end projecting above the cork.", "fibs": ["cork"]}
{"text": "A paper scale may be put inside the bottle in advance to measure the separation of leaves.", "fibs": ["paper"]}
{"text": "The separation is a rough measure of the amount of charge on the electroscope.", "fibs": ["separation"]}
{"text": "Figure 1.2 Electroscopes: (a) The gold leaf electroscope, (b) Schematics of a simple electroscope.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "To understand how the electroscope works, use the white paper strips we used for seeing the attraction of charged bodies.", "fibs": ["electroscope"]}
{"text": "Fold the strips into half so that you make a mark of fold.", "fibs": ["half"]}
{"text": "Open the strip and iron it lightly with the mountain fold up, as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["strip"]}
{"text": "Hold the strip by pinching it at the fold.", "fibs": ["strip"]}
{"text": "You would notice that the two halves move apart.", "fibs": ["notice"]}
{"text": "This shows that the strip has acquired charge on ironing.", "fibs": ["strip"]}
{"text": "When you fold it into half, both the halves have the same charge.", "fibs": ["half"]}
{"text": "The same effect is seen in the leaf electroscope.", "fibs": ["effect"]}
{"text": "On charging the curtain rod by touching the ball end with an electrified body, charge is transferred to the curtain rod and the attached aluminium foil.", "fibs": ["curtain"]}
{"text": "Both the halves of the foil get similar charge and therefore repel each other.", "fibs": ["foil"]}
{"text": "The divergence in the leaves depends on the amount of charge on them.", "fibs": ["divergence"]}
{"text": "Let us first try to understand why material bodies acquire charge.", "fibs": ["material"]}
{"text": "You know that all matter is made up of atoms and/or molecules.", "fibs": ["matter"]}
{"text": "Forces that hold the molecules together, forces that hold atoms together in a solid, the adhesive force of glue, forces associated with surface tension, all are basically electrical in nature, arising from the forces between charged particles.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "Thus the electric force is all pervasive and it encompasses almost each and every field associated with our life.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "It is therefore  essential that we learn more about such a force.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "Figure 1.3 Paper strip experiment.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "To electrify a neutral body, we need to add or remove one kind of charge.", "fibs": ["body"]}
{"text": "When we say that a body is charged, we always refer to this excess charge or deficit of charge.", "fibs": ["body"]}
{"text": "In solids,  some of the electrons, being  less tightly bound in the atom, are the charges which are transferred from one body to the other.", "fibs": ["atom"]}
{"text": "A body can thus be charged positively by losing some of its electrons.", "fibs": ["body"]}
{"text": "Similarly, a body can be charged negatively by gaining electrons.", "fibs": ["body"]}
{"text": "When we rub a glass rod with silk, some of the electrons from the rod are transferred to the silk cloth.", "fibs": ["rub"]}
{"text": "Thus the rod gets positively charged and the silk gets negatively charged.", "fibs": ["rod"]}
{"text": "No new charge is created in the process of rubbing.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "Also the number of electrons, that are transferred, is a very small fraction of the total number of electrons in the material body.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "Also only the less tightly bound electrons in a material body can be transferred from it to another by rubbing.", "fibs": ["material"]}
{"text": "Therefore, when a body is rubbed with another, the bodies get charged and that is why we have to stick to certain pairs of materials to notice charging on rubbing the bodies.", "fibs": ["body"]}
{"text": "1.3  Conductors and Insulators
A metal rod held in hand and rubbed with wool will not show any sign of being charged.", "fibs": ["metal"]}
{"text": "However, if a metal rod with a wooden or plastic handle is rubbed without touching its metal part, it shows signs of charging.", "fibs": ["metal"]}
{"text": "Suppose we connect one end of a copper wire to a neutral pith ball and the other end to a negatively charged plastic rod.", "fibs": ["end"]}
{"text": "We will find that the pith ball acquires a negative charge.", "fibs": ["pith"]}
{"text": "If a similar experiment is repeated with a nylon thread or a rubber band, no transfer of charge will take place from the plastic rod to the pith ball.", "fibs": ["experiment"]}
{"text": "Why does the transfer of charge not take place from the rod to the ball?", "fibs": ["transfer"]}
{"text": "Some substances readily allow passage of electricity through them, others do not.", "fibs": ["passage"]}
{"text": "Those which allow electricity to pass through them easily are called conductors.", "fibs": ["electricity"]}
{"text": "They have electric charges (electrons) that are comparatively free to move inside the material.", "fibs": ["move"]}
{"text": "Metals, human and animal bodies and earth are conductors.", "fibs": ["animal"]}
{"text": "Most of the non-metals like glass, porcelain, plastic, nylon, wood offer high resistance to the passage of electricity through them.", "fibs": ["glass"]}
{"text": "Most  substances fall into one of the two classes stated above*.", "fibs": ["fall"]}
{"text": "When some charge is transferred to a conductor, it readily gets distributed over the entire surface of the conductor.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "In contrast, if some charge is put on an insulator, it stays at the same place.", "fibs": ["contrast"]}
{"text": "You will learn why this happens in the next chapter.", "fibs": ["chapter"]}
{"text": "This property of the materials tells you why a nylon or plastic comb gets electrified on combing dry hair or on rubbing, but a metal article like spoon does not.", "fibs": ["property"]}
{"text": "The charges on metal leak through our body to the ground as both are conductors of electricity.", "fibs": ["metal"]}
{"text": "When we bring a charged body  in contact with the earth,  all the excess charge on the body disappears by causing a momentary current to pass to the ground through the connecting conductor (such as our body).", "fibs": ["body"]}
{"text": "This process of sharing the charges with the earth is called grounding or earthing.", "fibs": ["process"]}
{"text": "Earthing provides a safety measure for electrical circuits and appliances.", "fibs": ["safety"]}
{"text": "A thick metal plate is buried deep into the earth and thick wires are drawn from this plate; these are  used in buildings  for the purpose of earthing near the mains supply.", "fibs": ["metal"]}
{"text": "The electric wiring in our houses has three wires: live, neutral and earth.", "fibs": ["wiring"]}
{"text": "The first two carry electric current from the power station and the third is earthed by connecting it to the buried metal plate.", "fibs": ["power"]}
{"text": "Metallic bodies of the electric appliances such as electric iron, refrigerator, TV are connected to the earth wire.", "fibs": ["iron"]}
{"text": "When any fault occurs or live wire touches the metallic body, the charge flows to the earth without damaging the appliance and without causing any injury to the humans; this  would have otherwise been unavoidable since  the human body is a  conductor of electricity.", "fibs": ["fault"]}
{"text": "* There is a third category called semiconductors, which offer resistance to the movement of charges which is intermediate between the conductors and insulators.", "fibs": ["category"]}
{"text": "1.4  Charging by Induction
When we touch a pith ball with an electrified plastic rod, some of the negative charges on the rod are transferred to the pith ball and it also gets charged.", "fibs": ["touch"]}
{"text": "Thus the pith ball is charged by contact.", "fibs": ["pith"]}
{"text": "It is then repelled by the plastic rod but is attracted by a glass rod which is oppositely charged.", "fibs": ["plastic"]}
{"text": "However, why a electrified rod attracts light objects, is  a  question we have still left unanswered.", "fibs": ["rod"]}
{"text": "Let us try to understand what could be happening by performing the following experiment.", "fibs": ["experiment"]}
{"text": "Figure 1.4 Charging by induction.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "(i)	Bring two metal spheres, A and B, supported on insulating stands, in contact as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["metal"]}
{"text": "1.4(a).", "fibs": ["1.4(a"]}
{"text": "(ii)	Bring a positively charged rod near one of the spheres, say A, taking care that it does not touch the sphere.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "The free electrons in the spheres are attracted towards the rod.", "fibs": ["rod"]}
{"text": "This leaves an excess of positive charge on the rear surface of sphere B.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "Both kinds of charges are bound in the metal spheres and cannot escape.", "fibs": ["metal"]}
{"text": "They, therefore, reside on the surfaces, as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "1.4(b).", "fibs": ["1.4(b"]}
{"text": "The left surface of sphere A, has an excess of negative charge and the right surface of sphere B, has an excess of positive charge.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "However, not all of the electrons in the spheres have accumulated on the left surface of A.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "As the negative charge starts building up at the left surface of A, other electrons are repelled by these.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "In a short time, equilibrium is reached under the action of force of attraction of the rod and the force of repulsion due to the accumulated charges.", "fibs": ["time"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "1.4(b) shows the equilibrium situation.", "fibs": ["1.4(b"]}
{"text": "The process is called induction of charge and happens almost instantly.", "fibs": ["process"]}
{"text": "The accumulated charges remain on the surface, as shown, till the glass rod is held near the sphere.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "If the rod is removed, the charges are not acted by any outside force and they redistribute to their original neutral state.", "fibs": ["rod"]}
{"text": "(iii)	Separate the spheres by a small distance while the glass rod is still held near sphere A, as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "1.4(c).", "fibs": ["1.4(c"]}
{"text": "(iv)	Remove the rod.", "fibs": ["iv"]}
{"text": "The charges on spheres rearrange themselves as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "1.4(d).", "fibs": ["1.4(d"]}
{"text": "The charges on them get uniformly distributed over them, as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "1.4(e).", "fibs": ["1.4(e"]}
{"text": "In this process, the metal spheres will each be equal and oppositely charged.", "fibs": ["process"]}
{"text": "This is charging by induction.", "fibs": ["induction"]}
{"text": "The positively charged glass rod does not lose any of its charge, contrary to the process of charging by contact.", "fibs": ["glass"]}
{"text": "When electrified rods are brought near light objects, a similar effect takes place.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "The rods induce opposite charges on the near surfaces of the objects and similar charges move to the farther side of the object.", "fibs": ["move"]}
{"text": "[This happens even when the light object is not a conductor.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "The mechanism for how this happens is explained later in Sections 1.10 and 2.10.]", "fibs": ["mechanism"]}
{"text": "However, the magnitude of force depends on the distance between the charges and in this case the force of attraction overweighs the force of repulsion.", "fibs": ["magnitude"]}
{"text": "As a result the particles like bits of paper or pith balls, being light, are pulled towards the rods.", "fibs": ["result"]}
{"text": "Example 1.1 How can you charge a metal sphere positively without touching it?", "fibs": ["Example"]}
{"text": "Solution Figure 1.5(a) shows an uncharged metallic sphere on an insulating metal stand.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "Bring a negatively charged rod close to the metallic sphere, as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["rod"]}
{"text": "1.5(b).", "fibs": ["1.5(b"]}
{"text": "As the rod is brought close to the sphere, the free electrons in the sphere move away due to repulsion and start piling up at the farther end.", "fibs": ["rod"]}
{"text": "The near end becomes positively charged due to deficit of electrons.", "fibs": ["end"]}
{"text": "This process of charge distribution stops when the net force on the free electrons inside the metal is zero.", "fibs": ["process"]}
{"text": "Connect the sphere to the ground by a conducting wire.", "fibs": ["sphere"]}
{"text": "The electrons will flow to the ground while the positive charges at the near end will remain held there due to the attractive force of the negative charges on the rod, as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["flow"]}
{"text": "1.5(c).", "fibs": ["1.5(c"]}
{"text": "Disconnect the sphere from the ground.", "fibs": ["sphere"]}
{"text": "The positive charge continues to be held at the near end [Fig.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "1.5(d)].", "fibs": ["1.5(d"]}
{"text": "Remove the electrified rod.", "fibs": ["rod"]}
{"text": "The positive charge will spread uniformly over the sphere as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "1.5(e).", "fibs": ["1.5(e"]}
{"text": "Figure 1.5
In this experiment, the metal sphere gets charged by the process of induction and the rod does not lose any of its charge.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "Similar steps are involved in charging a metal sphere negatively by induction, by bringing a positively charged rod near it.", "fibs": ["metal"]}
{"text": "In this case the electrons will flow from the ground to the sphere when the sphere is connected to the ground with a wire.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "Here,  we shall now describe some other properties of the electric charge.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "If the sizes of charged bodies are very small as compared to the distances between them, we treat them as point charges.", "fibs": ["point"]}
{"text": "All the charge content of the body is assumed to be concentrated at one point in space.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "1.5.1 Additivity of charges
We have not as yet given a quantitative definition of a charge; we shall follow it up in the next section.", "fibs": ["definition"]}
{"text": "If a system contains two point charges q1 and q2, the total charge of the system is obtained simply by adding algebraically q1 and q2 , i.e., charges add up like real numbers or they are scalars like the mass of a body.", "fibs": ["system"]}
{"text": "If a system contains n charges q1, q2, q3, …, qn, then the total charge of the system is q1 + q2 + q3 + … + qn .", "fibs": ["system"]}
{"text": "Charge has  magnitude but no direction, similar to mass.", "fibs": ["magnitude"]}
{"text": "However, there is one difference between mass and charge.", "fibs": ["difference"]}
{"text": "Mass of a body is always positive whereas a charge can be either positive or negative.", "fibs": ["body"]}
{"text": "Proper signs have to be used while adding the charges in a system.", "fibs": ["system"]}
{"text": "For example, the total charge of a system containing five charges +1, +2, –3, +4 and –5, in some arbitrary unit, is (+1) + (+2) + (–3) + (+4) + (–5) = –1 in the same unit.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "1.5.2 Charge is conserved
We have already  hinted to the fact that when bodies are charged by rubbing, there is transfer of electrons from one body to the other; no new charges are either created or destroyed.", "fibs": ["fact"]}
{"text": "A picture of particles of electric charge enables us to understand the idea of conservation of charge.", "fibs": ["picture"]}
{"text": "When we rub two bodies, what one body gains in charge the other body loses.", "fibs": ["rub"]}
{"text": "Within an isolated system consisting of many charged bodies, due to interactions among the bodies, charges may get redistributed but it is found that the total charge of the isolated system is always conserved.", "fibs": ["system"]}
{"text": "Conservation of charge has been established experimentally.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "It is not possible to create or destroy net charge carried by any isolated system although the charge carrying particles may be created or destroyed in a process.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "Sometimes nature creates charged particles: a neutron turns into a proton and an electron.", "fibs": ["nature"]}
{"text": "The proton and electron thus created have equal and opposite charges and the total charge is zero before and after the creation.", "fibs": ["proton"]}
{"text": "1.5.3 Quantisation of charge
Experimentally it is established that all free charges are integral multiples of a basic unit of charge denoted by e. Thus charge q on a body is always given by
q = ne
where n is any integer, positive or negative.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "This basic unit of charge is the charge that an electron or proton carries.", "fibs": ["unit"]}
{"text": "By convention, the charge on an electron is taken to be negative; therefore charge on an electron is written as –e and that on a proton as +e.", "fibs": ["convention"]}
{"text": "The fact that electric charge is always an integral multiple of e is termed as quantisation of charge.", "fibs": ["fact"]}
{"text": "There are a large number of situations in physics where certain physical quantities are quantised.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "The quantisation of charge was first suggested by the experimental laws of electrolysis discovered by English experimentalist Faraday.", "fibs": ["quantisation"]}
{"text": "In the International System (SI) of Units, a unit of charge is called a coulomb and is denoted by the symbol C. A coulomb is defined in terms the unit of the electric current which you are going to learn in a subsequent chapter.", "fibs": ["SI"]}
{"text": "In terms of this definition, one coulomb is the charge flowing through a wire in 1 s if the current is 1 A (ampere), (see Chapter 2 of Class XI, Physics Textbook , Part I).", "fibs": ["definition"]}
{"text": "In this system, the value of the basic unit of charge is 
e = 1.602192 × 10–19 C
Thus, there are about 6 × 1018 electrons in a charge of  –1C.", "fibs": ["system"]}
{"text": "In electrostatics, charges of this large magnitude are seldom encountered and hence we use smaller units 1 µC (micro coulomb) = 10–6 C or 1 mC (milli coulomb) = 10–3 C. 
If the protons and electrons are the only basic charges in the universe, all the observable charges have to be integral multiples of e. Thus, if a body contains n1 electrons and n2 protons, the total amount of charge on the body is n2 × e + n1 × (–e) = (n2 – n1) e. Since n1 and n2 are integers, their difference is also an integer.", "fibs": ["magnitude"]}
{"text": "Thus the charge on any body is always an integral multiple of e and can be increased or decreased also in steps of e. 
The step size e is, however, very small because at the macroscopic level, we deal with charges of a few µC.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "At this scale the fact that charge of a body can increase or decrease in units of e is not visible.", "fibs": ["scale"]}
{"text": "In this respect, the grainy nature of the charge is lost and it appears to be continuous.", "fibs": ["respect"]}
{"text": "This situation can be compared with the geometrical concepts of points and lines.", "fibs": ["situation"]}
{"text": "A dotted line viewed from a distance appears continuous to us but is not continuous in reality.", "fibs": ["line"]}
{"text": "As many points very close to each other normally give an impression of a continuous line, many small charges taken together appear as a continuous charge distribution.", "fibs": ["impression"]}
{"text": "At the macroscopic level, one deals with charges that are enormous compared to the magnitude of charge e. Since e = 1.6 × 10–19 C, a charge of magnitude, say 1 µC, contains something like 1013 times the electronic charge.", "fibs": ["macroscopic"]}
{"text": "At this scale, the fact that charge can increase or decrease only in units of e is not very different from saying that charge can take continuous values.", "fibs": ["scale"]}
{"text": "Thus, at the macroscopic level, the quantisation of charge has no practical consequence and can be ignored.", "fibs": ["macroscopic"]}
{"text": "However, at the microscopic level, where the charges involved are of the order of a few tens or hundreds of e, i.e., they can be counted, they appear in discrete lumps and quantisation of charge cannot be ignored.", "fibs": ["level"]}
{"text": "It is the magnitude of scale involved that is very important.", "fibs": ["magnitude"]}
{"text": "Example 1.2 If 109 electrons move out of a body to another body every second, how much time is required to get a total charge of 1 C on the other body?", "fibs": ["Example"]}
{"text": "Solution In one second 109 electrons move out of the body.", "fibs": ["move"]}
{"text": "Therefore the charge given out in one second is 1.6 × 10–19 × 109 C = 1.6 × 10–10 C. 
The time required to accumulate a charge of 1 C can then be estimated to be 1 C ÷ (1.6 × 10–10 C/s) = 6.25 × 109 s = 6.25 × 109 ÷ (365 × 24 × 3600) years = 198 years.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "Thus to collect a charge of one coulomb, from a body from which 109 electrons move out every second, we will need approximately 200 years.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "One coulomb is, therefore, a very large unit for many practical purposes.", "fibs": ["coulomb"]}
{"text": "It is, however, also important to know what is roughly the number of electrons contained in a piece of one cubic centimetre of a material.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "A cubic piece of copper of side 1 cm contains about 2.5 × 1024 electrons.", "fibs": ["piece"]}
{"text": "Example 1.3 How much positive and negative charge is there in a cup of water?", "fibs": ["Example"]}
{"text": "Solution Let us assume that the mass of one cup of water is 250 g. The molecular mass of water is 18g.", "fibs": ["mass"]}
{"text": "Thus, one mole (= 6.02 × 1023 molecules) of water is 18 g. Therefore the number of molecules in one cup of water is (250/18) × 6.02 × 1023.", "fibs": ["mole"]}
{"text": "Each molecule of water contains two hydrogen atoms and one oxygen atom, i.e., 10 electrons and 10 protons.", "fibs": ["molecule"]}
{"text": "Hence the total positive and total negative charge has the same magnitude.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "It is equal to (250/18) × 6.02 × 1023 × 10 × 1.6 × 10–19 C = 1.34 × 107 C.


