How did Coulomb arrive at this law from his experiments?", "fibs": ["point"]}
{"text": "Coulomb used a torsion balance*  for measuring the force between two charged metallic spheres.", "fibs": ["torsion"]}
{"text": "When the separation between two spheres is much larger than the radius of each sphere, the charged spheres may be regarded as point charges.", "fibs": ["separation"]}
{"text": "How then could he discover a relation like Eq.", "fibs": ["relation"]}
{"text": "Coulomb thought of the following simple way: Suppose the charge on a metallic sphere is q.", "fibs": ["way"]}
{"text": "If the sphere is put in contact with an identical uncharged sphere, the charge will spread over the two spheres.", "fibs": ["sphere"]}
{"text": "By symmetry, the charge on each sphere will be q/2*.", "fibs": ["symmetry"]}
{"text": "Repeating this process, we can get charges q/2, q/4, etc.", "fibs": ["process"]}
{"text": "Coulomb varied the distance for a fixed pair of charges and measured the force for different separations.", "fibs": ["distance"]}
{"text": "He then varied the charges in pairs, keeping the distance fixed for each pair.", "fibs": ["distance"]}
{"text": "Comparing forces for different pairs of charges at different distances, Coulomb arrived at the relation, Eq.", "fibs": ["relation"]}
{"text": "* A torsion balance is a sensitive device to measure force.", "fibs": ["torsion"]}
{"text": "It was also used later by Cavendish to measure the very feeble gravitational force between two objects, to verify Newton’s Law of Gravitation.", "fibs": ["measure"]}
{"text": "Coulomb’s law, a simple mathematical statement,  was initially experimentally arrived at  in the manner described above.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "While the original experiments established it at a macroscopic scale, it has also been established down to subatomic level  (r ~ 10–10 m).", "fibs": ["macroscopic"]}
{"text": "Coulomb discovered his law without knowing the explicit magnitude of the charge.", "fibs": ["law"]}
{"text": "In fact, it is the other way round: Coulomb’s law can now be employed to furnish a definition for a unit of charge.", "fibs": ["fact"]}
{"text": "In the relation, Eq.", "fibs": ["relation"]}
