Charles Augustin de Coulomb (1736 – 1806) Coulomb, a French physicist, began his career as a military engineer in the West Indies.", "fibs": ["q1"]}
{"text": "In 1776, he returned to Paris and retired to a small estate to do his scientific research.", "fibs": ["estate"]}
{"text": "He invented a torsion balance to measure the quantity of a force and used it for determination of forces of electric attraction or repulsion between small charged spheres.", "fibs": ["torsion"]}
{"text": "He thus arrived in 1785 at the inverse square law relation, now known as Coulomb’s law.", "fibs": ["square"]}
{"text": "The law had been anticipated by Priestley and also by Cavendish earlier, though Cavendish never published his results.", "fibs": ["law"]}
{"text": "Coulomb also found the inverse square law of force between unlike and like magnetic poles.", "fibs": ["square"]}
{"text": "That is, 1 C is the charge that when placed at a distance of 1 m from another charge of the same magnitude in vacuum experiences an electrical force of repulsion of magnitude 9 × 109 N. One coulomb is evidently too big a unit to be used.", "fibs": ["C"]}
{"text": "In practice, in electrostatics, one uses smaller units like 1 mC or 1 µC.", "fibs": ["practice"]}
