1.11.2 Physical significance of dipoles

In most molecules, the centres of positive charges and of negative charges* lie at the same place.", "fibs": ["r."]}
{"text": "Therefore, their dipole moment is zero.", "fibs": ["moment"]}
{"text": "CO2 and CH4 are of this type of molecules.", "fibs": ["CO2"]}
{"text": "However, they develop a dipole moment when an electric field is applied.", "fibs": ["moment"]}
{"text": "Therefore they have a permanent electric dipole moment, even in the absence of an electric field.", "fibs": ["moment"]}
{"text": "Water molecules, H2O, is an example of this type.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Various materials give rise to interesting properties and important applications in the presence or absence of electric field.", "fibs": ["rise"]}
