{"text": "1.12 Dipole in a Uniform External Field
Consider a permanent dipole of dipole moment p in a uniform external field E, as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["moment"]}
{"text": "(By permanent dipole, we mean that p exists irrespective of E; it has not been induced byE.)", "fibs": ["p"]}
{"text": "There is a force qE on q and a force –qE on –q.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "The net force on the dipole is zero, since E is uniform.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "However, the charges are separated, so the forces act at different points, resulting in a torque on the dipole.", "fibs": ["act"]}
{"text": "When the net force is zero, the torque (couple) is independent of the origin.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "Its magnitude equals the magnitude of each force multiplied by the arm of the couple (perpendicular distance between the two antiparallel forces).", "fibs": ["magnitude"]}
{"text": "Figure 1.22 Dipole in a uniform electric field.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "Magnitude of torque = q E × 2 a sinθ
= 2 q a E sinθ
Its direction is normal to the plane of the paper, coming out of it.", "fibs": ["Magnitude"]}
{"text": "The magnitude of p × E is also p E sinθ and its direction is normal to the paper, coming out of it.", "fibs": ["magnitude"]}
{"text": "Thus,
τ = p × E	(1.22)
This torque will tend to align the dipole with the field E. When p is aligned with E, the torque is zero.", "fibs": ["τ"]}
{"text": "What happens if the field is not uniform?", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "In that case, the net force will evidently be non-zero.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "In addition there will, in general, be a torque on the system as before.", "fibs": ["addition"]}
{"text": "The general case is involved, so let us consider the simpler situations when p is parallel to E or antiparallel to E. In either case, the net torque is zero, but there is a net force on the dipole if E is not uniform.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "Figure 1.23 is self-explanatory.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "It is easily seen that when p is parallel to E, the dipole has a net force in the direction of increasing field.", "fibs": ["p"]}
{"text": "When p is antiparallel to E, the net force on the dipole is in the direction of decreasing field.", "fibs": ["p"]}
{"text": "In general, the force depends on the orientation of p with respect to E.

This brings us to a common observation in frictional electricity.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "A comb run through dry hair attracts pieces of paper.", "fibs": ["comb"]}
{"text": "The comb, as we know, acquires charge through friction.", "fibs": ["comb"]}
{"text": "But the paper is not charged.", "fibs": ["paper"]}
{"text": "What then explains the attractive force?", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "Taking the clue from the preceding discussion, the charged comb ‘polarises’ the piece of paper, i.e., induces a net dipole moment in the direction of field.", "fibs": ["clue"]}
{"text": "Further, the electric field due to the comb is not uniform.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "In this situation, it is easily seen that the paper should move in the direction of the comb!", "fibs": ["situation"]}
{"text": "1.13 Continuous Charge Distribution
We have so far dealt with charge configurations involving discrete charges q1, q2, ..., qn.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "One reason why we restricted to discrete charges is that the mathematical treatment is simpler and does not involve calculus.", "fibs": ["reason"]}
{"text": "For many purposes, however, it is impractical to work in terms of discrete charges and we need to work with continuous charge distributions.", "fibs": ["work"]}
{"text": "For example, on the surface of a charged conductor, it is impractical to specify the charge distribution in terms of the locations of the microscopic charged constituents.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "It is more feasible to consider an area element ∆S (Fig.", "fibs": ["area"]}
{"text": "1.24) on the surface of the conductor (which is very small on the macroscopic scale but big enough to include a very large number of electrons) and specify the charge ∆Q on that element.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "We then define a surface charge density σ at the area element by





