We can do this at different points on the conductor and thus arrive at a continuous function σ, called the surface charge density.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "The surface charge density σ so defined ignores the quantisation of charge and the discontinuity in charge distribution at the microscopic level*.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "σrepresents macroscopic surface charge density, which in a sense, is a smoothed out average of the microscopic charge density over an area element ∆S which, as said before, is large microscopically but small macroscopically.", "fibs": ["macroscopic"]}
{"text": "The units for σ are C/m2.", "fibs": ["σ"]}
