The law implies that the total electric flux through a closed surface is zero if no charge is enclosed by the surface.", "fibs": ["state"]}
{"text": "We can see that explicitly in the simple situation of Fig.", "fibs": ["situation"]}
{"text": "Here the electric field is uniform and we are considering a closed cylindrical surface, with its axis parallel to the uniform field E. The total flux φ through the surface is φ = φ1 + φ2 + φ3, where φ1 and φ2 represent the flux through the surfaces 1 and 2 (of circular cross-section) of the cylinder and φ3 is the flux through the curved cylindrical part of the closed surface.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "Now the normal to the surface 3 at every point is perpendicular to E, so by definition of flux, φ3 = 0.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "Further, the outward normal to 2 is along E while the outward normal to 1 is opposite to E. Therefore,
φ1 = –E S1, φ2 = +E S2
S1 = S2 = S
where S is the area of circular cross-section.", "fibs": ["E"]}
{"text": "Thus, the total flux is zero, as expected by Gauss’s law.", "fibs": ["flux"]}
{"text": "Thus, whenever you find that the net electric flux through a closed surface is zero, we conclude that the total charge contained in the closed surface is zero.", "fibs": ["flux"]}
{"text": "The great significance of Gauss’s law Eq.", "fibs": ["significance"]}
{"text": "Let us note some important points regarding this law:
(i)	Gauss’s law is true for any closed surface, no matter what its shape or size.", "fibs": ["note"]}
{"text": "(ii)	The term q on the right side of Gauss’s law, Eq.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "(1.31), includes the sum of all charges enclosed by the surface.", "fibs": ["sum"]}
{"text": "The charges may be located anywhere inside the surface.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "(iii)	In the situation when the surface is so chosen that there are some charges inside and some outside, the electric field [whose flux appears on the left side of Eq.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "(1.31)] is due to all the charges, both inside and outside S. The term q on the right side of Gauss’s law, however, represents only the total charge inside S.
(iv)	The surface that we choose for the application of Gauss’s law is called the Gaussian surface.", "fibs": ["term"]}
{"text": "You may choose any Gaussian surface and apply Gauss’s law.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "However, take care not to let the Gaussian surface pass through any discrete charge.", "fibs": ["care"]}
