{"text": "On symmetry operations
In Physics, we often encounter systems with various symmetries.", "fibs": ["symmetry"]}
{"text": "Consideration of these symmetries helps one arrive at results much faster than otherwise by a straightforward calculation.", "fibs": ["Consideration"]}
{"text": "Consider, for example an infinite uniform sheet of charge (surface charge densityσ) along the y-z plane.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "This system is unchanged if (a) translated parallel to the y-z plane in any direction, (b) rotated about the x-axis through any angle.", "fibs": ["system"]}
{"text": "As the system is unchanged under such symmetry operation, so must its properties be.", "fibs": ["system"]}
{"text": "In particular, in this example, the electric field E must be unchanged.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Translation symmetry along the y-axis shows that the electric field must be the same at a point (0, y1, 0) as at (0, y2, 0).", "fibs": ["symmetry"]}
{"text": "Similarly translational symmetry along the z-axis shows that the electric field at two point (0, 0, z1) and (0, 0, z2) must be the same.", "fibs": ["symmetry"]}
{"text": "By using rotation symmetry around the x-axis, we can conclude that E must be perpendicular to the y-z plane, that is, it must be parallel to the x-direction.", "fibs": ["rotation"]}
{"text": "Try to think of a symmetry now which will tell you that the magnitude of the electric field is a constant, independent of the x-coordinate.", "fibs": ["symmetry"]}
{"text": "It thus turns out that the magnitude of the electric field due to a uniformly charged infinite conducting sheet is the same at all points in space.", "fibs": ["magnitude"]}
{"text": "The direction, however, is opposite of each other on either side ofthe sheet.", "fibs": ["direction"]}
{"text": "Compare this with the effort needed to arrive at this result by a direct calculation using Coulomb’s law.", "fibs": ["effort"]}
{"text": "Electric and magnetic forces determine the properties of atoms, molecules and bulk matter.", "fibs": ["bulk"]}
{"text": "From simple experiments on frictional electricity, one can infer that there are two types of charges in nature; and that like charges repel and unlike charges attract.", "fibs": ["electricity"]}
{"text": "By convention, the charge on a glass rod rubbed with silk is positive; that on a plastic rod rubbed with fur is then negative.", "fibs": ["convention"]}
{"text": "Conductors allow movement of electric charge through them, insulators do not.", "fibs": ["movement"]}
{"text": "Electric charge has three basic properties: quantisation, additivity and conservation.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "Quantisation of electric charge means that total charge (q) of a body is always an integral multiple of a basic quantum of charge (e) i.e., q = n e, where n = 0, ±1, ±2, ±3, .... Proton and electron have charges +e, –e, respectively.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "For macroscopic charges for which n is a very large number, quantisation of charge can be ignored.", "fibs": ["macroscopic"]}
{"text": "Additivity of electric charges means that the total charge of a system is the algebraic sum (i.e., the sum taking into account proper signs) of all individual charges in the system.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "Conservation of electric charges means that the total charge of an isolated system remains unchanged with time.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "This means that when bodies are charged through friction, there is a transfer of electric charge from one body to another, but no creation or destruction of charge.", "fibs": ["friction"]}
{"text": "Coulomb’s Law: The mutual electrostatic force between two point charges q1 and q2 is proportional to the product q1q2 and inversely proportional to the square of the distance r21separating them.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "Mathematically,
