{"text": "Superposition Principle: The principle is based on the property that the forces with which two charges attract or repel each other are not affected by the presence of a third (or more) additional charge(s).", "fibs": ["Superposition"]}
{"text": "For an assembly of charges q1, q2, q3, ..., the force on any charge, sayq1, is the vector sum of the force on q1 due to q2, the force on q1 due to q3, and so on.", "fibs": ["assembly"]}
{"text": "For each pair, the force is given by the Coulomb’s law for two charges stated earlier.", "fibs": ["pair"]}
{"text": "The electric field E at a point due to a charge configuration is the force on a small positive test charge q placed at the point divided by the magnitude of the charge.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "Electric field due to a point charge q has a magnitude |q|/4πε0r2; it is radially outwards from q, if q is positive, and radially inwards if q is negative.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "Like Coulomb force, electric field also satisfies superposition principle.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "An electric field line is a curve drawn in such a way that the tangent at each point on the curve gives the direction of electric field at that point.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "The relative closeness of field lines indicates the relative strength of electric field at different points; they crowd near each other in regions of strong electric field and are far apart where the electric field is weak.", "fibs": ["closeness"]}
{"text": "In regions of constant electric field, the field lines are uniformly spaced parallel straight lines.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "Some of the important properties of field lines are: (i) Field lines are continuous curves without any breaks.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "(ii) Two field lines cannot cross each other.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "(iii) Electrostatic field lines start at positive charges and end at negative charges —they cannot form closed loops.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "An electric dipole is a pair of equal and opposite charges q and –q separated by some distance 2a.", "fibs": ["pair"]}
{"text": "Its dipole moment vector p has magnitude 2qa and is in the direction of the dipole axis from –q to q.", "fibs": ["moment"]}
